Principal Component Analysis: Indian Stock Market

by JUMEX365

Dataset Description

stock <- read.csv("BRITANNIA.csv")[,1:12]
stock$Date <- ymd(stock$Date)

The dataset contains the price history and trading volumes of the BRITTANIA stocks from the index NIFTY 50 from NSE (National Stock Exchange) India. This dataset is a part of NIFTY-50 Stock Market Data (2000 - 2021) database.

“NIFTY-50 Stock Market Data: BRITANNIA” dataset contains 5305 stock market observations of Britannia Industries Ltd from 3 Jan 2000 to 30 Apr 2021.

Variables in dataset:

  1. Date - Date [datetime]

  2. Symbol - Symbol [character]

  3. Series - Type of security [factor]

  4. Close - Previous day’s close price [numeric]

  5. Open - Open price of day [numeric]

  6. High - Highest price in day [numeric]

  7. Low - Lowest price in day [numeric]

  8. Last - Last traded price in day [numeric]

  9. Close - Close price of day [numeric]

  10. VWAP - ratio of the cumulative share price to the cumulative volume traded over a given time period (Volume Weighted Average Price) [numeric]

  11. Volume - the total number of shares that have been bought or sold in a specific period of time or during the trading day [numeric]

  12. Turnover - the value of domestic shares traded divided by their market capitalization [numeric]

In this case, PCA can help to identify the most important variables in the dataset, and reduce the number of dimensions to a more manageable level. PCA can be used to identify underlying factors or themes in the stock market that are driving returns. By using PCA to group stocks into similar clusters based on these underlying factors, investors can build more diversified portfolios that are better able to weather market fluctuations.PCA can also be used to identify common sources of risk in the stock market, such as interest rate changes or commodity price fluctuation

As it can be seen from the correlation plot - variables are highly correlated and therefore it cannot be used in models since multicollinearity problem. This is just an example of how PCA can be useful for such data.

There are clearly two groups of variables: the first is about prices and the second is about shares in stock market. So, 2 PC’s are expected.

PCA

Proceeding to Principal Component Analysis. How much variance do the PCs retain?

row.names(stock1) <- stock$Date
pca_scores <- prcomp(stock1)
cat("PC Eigenvalues\n")
## PC Eigenvalues
pca_scores$sdev ^ 2
## [1] 7.50248392269 1.46439993678 0.03091899765 0.00132798386 0.00042260099
## [6] 0.00032155407 0.00008690510 0.00002667084 0.00001142802

As expected, by eigenvalues there are only two first highly informative PC’s, others are quite useless. Let’s visualize this.

fviz_screeplot(pca_scores, ncp=9)

By screeplot it can be seen that most of the variance is explained by the first principal component, second explains less and others - almost none.

stock_graphs <- PCA(stock1, graph = F)

fviz_pca_var(stock_graphs, col.var="contrib")

PC1: This principal component is mostly driven by Prev.Close, Open, High, Low, Last, and Close, which are all positively correlated with it. This component could represent overall market trend or general movement of stock prices.

PC2: This component is mostly driven by Volume and Turnover, which are both negatively correlated with it. This component could represent trading activity or liquidity.

Most of the variance is explained by the Stock Price changing as we can see by the “Variables - PCA” plot.

Conclusions

fviz_pca_biplot(pca_scores, col.var = "black", col.ind=year(stock$Date), labelsize = 2, repel = T, )

By biplot it can be seen that most outliers is the days with low PC2 - days when BRITANNIA has higher trading activity and higher PC1 - higher stock price. We can see that trading activity was higher in two periods - at the stock opening and in the last years. We can see that in years from 2000 to approximately 2017 the stock price has been generally increasing but the trading activity (Volume and Turnover) has been generally decreasing, but in the last years the price of stock and activity was kind of stabilizing at the middle and the most trading activity was in the last years - years of stabilizing of the price of stocks.
